Reasoning: The paper deals with algorithmic and complexity aspects of the Edge Disjoint Paths problem, which is a classic problem in graph theory. The use of structural parameterizations and the focus on treewidth and maximum degree suggest that the paper may belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) categories. The study of the augmented graph and the W[1]-hardness result suggest that Computational Geometry (cs.CG) and Graph Theory (cs.GT) may also be relevant sub-categories. Finally, the development of efficient algorithms and fixed-parameter tractability results suggest that Computational Complexity (cs.CC) may also be a relevant sub-category.
